Itâ€™s critically important to LOOK at what you have. Are there weird values? Has the match between taxa and state gone correctly? Do you think you have binary data, but thereâ€™s actually only state 1? Especially as data sets grow (yay), and are assembled using scripts rather than by error-prone, non-reproducable hands (double yay), scientists are increasingly less likely to deeply look at our data. Thatâ€™s bad â€“ donâ€™t be that person.

First, letâ€™s use parsimony to look at ancestral states:

cleaned.discrete <- as.matrix(CleanData$data)
cleaned.discrete.phyDat <- phangorn::phyDat(cleaned.discrete, type="USER", levels=c("0","1","2")) 
#phyDat is a data format used by phangorn
anc.p <- phangorn::ancestral.pars(CleanData$phy, cleaned.discrete.phyDat)
plotAnc(CleanData$phy, anc.p, 1, cex.pie=.5)

Do you see uncertainty? What does it mean? yes, at certain nodesâ€“ either state equally likely due to either state producing an equally parsimonius reconstruction

Now, plot the likelihood estimates.

anc.ml <- ancestral.pml(pml(CleanData$phy, cleaned.discrete.phyDat), type="ml")
plotAnc(CleanData$phy, anc.ml, 1, cex.pie=.5)

How does this differ from parsimony? less uncertainty at ancestral nodes

Why does it differ from parsimony? ancestral nodes in ML tree show probability of each state at ancestral node

What does uncertainty mean? there is a possibility that the ancestral node was a different state

Now, to the biological questions. For many of these, corHMM will be a useful package.

  1. How can you estimate transition rates between states? Do it.
cor.data <- cbind(row.names(CleanData$data),CleanData$data[,1])
cor.data.fake <- cor.data[,1:2]

for (i in 1:length(cor.data[,2])) {
  if (cor.data[i,2] == "2") {
    cor.data.fake[i,2] <- 1
  }
}

#cor.result <- corHMM(CleanData$phy, cor.data, rate.cat=1, node.states=c("joint"))
#only works for 2 char. states instead of original 3
cor.result1 <- corHMM(CleanData$phy, cor.data.fake, rate.cat=1, node.states=c("joint"))

  1. How could you examine if transition rates are equal? use p in corHMM to contrain the parameter for each transition rate between characters to be equal and compare AIC score to cor.result1 above

  2. Think about the Lewis (2001) MKV model. Are your traits all variable? Will using this make sense for your data? Try using it. Do results change? yes, the traits are variable.
